  "text": "It is well known that uptake of nanodrugs in cancer cells involves adenosine triphosphate (ATP)-dependent uptake mechanisms (i.e., dynamin-dependent), such as macropinocytosis, clathrin-coated pits, caveolae and associated intracellular trafficking of drugs in cancer cells were significantly different from the trends observed in normal cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Specifically, cancer cells typically exhibit highly upregulated amounts of membrane receptors, compared to normal cells, those membrane receptors mediate endocytosis, as they are necessary to maintain cellular energy metabolism for cancer survival [CITATION_5] . Therefore, internalized nanodrugs in cancer cells might experience more complex intracellular trafficking compared to that in normal cells. In addition, it has been well documented that cancer cells possess more endolysosomal compartments with acidic pH and abundant enzymes in the lysosomes (Lys), and exhibit higher redox potential (related to reduction/oxidation homeostasis) compared with normal cells [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . These differences manifest as varying levels of therapeutic nanodrug efficacy and can elicit selective toxicity to cancer and normal cells.",
